<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <p xml:id="PN393-intro">tiṇaiyum tuṟaiyum avai. cōḻaṉ kuḷaṟṟattuttuñciya kiḷḷivaḷavaṉai nalliṟaiyaṉār.
      </p>
      <p xml:lang="en">  
      </p>
    </div>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="PN393">
<l>patimutaṟ paḻakāp paḻaṅkaṇ vāḻkkaik</l>
<l>kuṟuneṭun tuṇaiyoṭu kūmai vītaliṟ</l>
<l>kuṭimuṟai pāṭi yoyyeṉa varunti</l>
<l>yaṭaṉacai maṟantaveṅ kuḻici malarkkum</l>
<l>kaṭaṉaṟi yāḷar piṟanāṭ ṭiṉmaiyiṉ</l>
<l>vaḷḷaṉ maiyiṉem varaivōr yāreṉa</l>
<l>vuḷḷiya vuḷḷamō ṭulainacai tuṇaiyā</l>
<l><gap quantity="3" reason="lost" unit="character"/>kavaka vellā morupāṟ paṭṭeṉa</l>
<l>malartā raṇṇaṉi ṉallicai yuḷḷi</l>
<l>yīrṅkai maṟantave ṉirumpē rokkal</l>
<l>kūrnta vevvamviṭak koḻuniṇaṅ kiḻippak</l>
<l>kōṭaip parutti vīṭuniṟai peyta</l>
<l>mūṭaip paṇṭa miṭainiṟain taṉṉa</l>
<l>veṇṇiṇa mūri yaruḷa nāḷuṟa</l>
<l>vīṉṟa varavi ṉāvuru kaṭukkumeṉ</l>
<l>ṟoṉṟupaṭu citāar tuvara nīkkip</l>
<l>pōtuviri pakaṉṟaip putumala raṉṉa</l>
<l>vakaṉṟumaṭi kaliṅka muṭīic celvamuṅ</l>
<l>kēṭiṉṟu nalkumati peruma māciṉ</l>
<l>matipurai mākkiṇai teḷirppa voṟṟi</l>
<l>yāṭumaka ḷalku loppa vāṭik</l>
<l>kōṭai yāyiṉuṅ kōṭi<gap quantity="13" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>kāviri purakku naṉṉāṭṭup poruna</l>
<l>vāyvāḷ vaḷavaṉ vāḻkeṉap</l>
<l>pīṭukeḻu nōṉṟāḷ pāṭukam palavē.</l>
</lg>
<lg xml:lang="en">
<l corresp="5">In the absence of other lands of men who know [their] duty </l>
<l corresp="4">who would make our pots bloom that have forgotten the longing to cook, </l>
<l corresp="3">suffering cruelly when singing in the order of hamlets/families, </l>
<l corresp="2">because of being destroyed by poverty(?) along with long and short companions, </l>
<l corresp="1">in a living in distress in unfamiliar places, </l>
<l corresp="7">as companion the longing for a fire place, with a heart that remembers, </l>
<l corresp="6">saying “who is there to keep us, out of generosity?”, </l>
<l corresp="8">………….. because all happens in one place </l>
<l corresp="9">o majesty with a flower garland, while, remembering your fame, </l>
<l corresp="10">my very big kinfolk that had forgotten moist hands </l>
<l corresp="11">tear greasy fat so that [their] abundant trouble lets go [of them], </l>
<l>as days occur when we are graced with pieces of white fat (14)</l>
<l>that are like densely filled stores in a receptacle (13)</l>
<l>into which the west wind had poured the dwindling fullness of cotton[-like clouds], (12)</l>
<l corresp="16">removing in pieces my old worn-out rags </l>
<l corresp="15">that resembled the tongues of birthing snakes, </l>
<l corresp="18">spreading out [and] putting on [me] a folded Kaliṅkam cloth </l>
<l corresp="17">that was like the new blossoms of the Pakaṉṟai that opens [its] buds, </l>
<l corresp="19a-c">grant without loss, o great man. </l>
<l corresp="19d-20">Pressing, so that it sounds, [my] big Kiṇai drum like the flawless moon, </l>
<l>dancing so as to match the hips of dancing girls, (21)</l>
<l corresp="22">even though there is west wind, a crore ………… </l>
<l corresp="23">o fighter of the good land that is guarded by the Kāviri, </l>
<l corresp="24">saying “may Vaḷavaṉ with an excellent sword live” </l>
<l corresp="25">on [your] sturdy feet that possess greatness we will sing many [songs]. </l>
</lg>
